{"cursor":"3349","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Christian Friedrich Ecklon' (ÃbenrÃ¥ 1795 â Cape Town 1868) was a Danish\nbotanical collector and apothecary.\n\nEcklon collected extensively in South Africa. His first visit was in 1823, as\nfirst an apothecary's apprentice and then pharmacist, looking for plants with\nmedicinal value. Lack of funding and a deteriorating health forced him to live\nin poor circumstances, selling bulbs or preparing herbal remedies. Nevertheless,\nwhen he returned to Europe in 1828, he had collected an extensive herbarium.\nDuring his stay in Hamburg, from 1833 to 1838, he worked on revising this\ncollection. This herbarium would become the basis for the [[Flora Capensis]]\n(1860â1865) by his friend, the Hamburg pharmacist Otto Wilhelm Sonder\n(1812â1881) in collaboration with the Irish botanist William Henry Harvey\n(1811â1866). The herbarium was later sold to Unio Itineraria, a WÃ¼rttemberg\nBotanical Society.\n\nEcklon was the author, with Karl Ludwig Philipp Zeyher who had travelled with\nhim from 1829, of Enumeratio Plantarum Africae Australis Extratropicae (1835-7),\na descriptive catalogue of South African plants. He later returned to South\nAfrica, where he died in 1868.\n\nThe herbaria of Lehmann and Sonder in the Swedish Museum of Natural History in\nStockholm gives special reference to the collection of Ecklon and Zeyher.\n\nOne of his pupils was Friedrich Heinrich Theodor Freese (c. 1795 â 1876), a\nGerman physicianâbotanist, who also studied South African plants.\n\nAccording to IPNI, Ecklon named a total of 1974 different genera or species.\n\nLike many botanists he was an entomologist making collections of plant\nassociated insects.\n\nThe genus [[Ecklonia]], including Ecklon's kelp (Ecklonia biruncinata or\n[[Ecklonia radiata|E. radiata]]), as well as Ecklon's Purple Iceplant\n([[Delosperma|Delosperma ecklonis]] 'Bright Eyes') and Ecklon's Everlasting\n([[Helichrysum|Helichrysum ecklonis]]) were named in his honour. This botanist\nis denoted by the author abbreviation ' Eckl. ' when citing a botanical\nname.\n","linknr":125,"url":"Christian_Friedrich_Ecklon","recorded":1376425243,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Christian_Friedrich_Ecklon&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Christian_Friedrich_Ecklon&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Friedrich_Ecklon","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Denmark","/wiki/Botany","/wiki/Apothecary","/wiki/South_Africa","/wiki/Pharmacist","/wiki/Bulb","/wiki/Herbarium","/wiki/Hamburg","/w/index.php?title=Flora_Capensis&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/Otto_Wilhelm_Sonder","/wiki/William_Henry_Harvey","/wiki/Unio_Itineraria","/wiki/W%C3%BCrttemberg","/wiki/Karl_Ludwig_Philipp_Zeyher","/wiki/Swedish_Museum_of_Natural_History","/wiki/Stockholm","/w/index.php?title=Friedrich_Heinrich_Theodor_Freese&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/IPNI","/wiki/Entomologist","/wiki/Ecklonia","/wiki/Ecklonia_radiata","/wiki/Delosperma","/wiki/Helichrysum","/wiki/List_of_botanists_by_author_abbreviation","/wiki/Author_citation_(botany